(1)	Hippocampus-PFC white matter connectivity; 
(2)	Amygdala-PFC white matter connectivity; 
(3)	Hippocampus-Amygdala white matter connectivity. 

White matter connectivity will be measured using probabilistic tractography that will be performed on collected diffusion tensor imaging data. Probabilistic tractography creates a density function for each subject that represents the probability that a voxel of a given seed mask will reach a specified target mask (Behrens et al, 2007; Greening &amp; Mitchell, 2015). In this study, we will map 7 white matter tracts (on each side) using probabilistic tractography with the amygdala and hippocampus separately as the seed regions. The PFC targets will be BA 9, 10, 11, 24, 25, 32, 47. These Brodmann’s Areas were chosen based on previous investigations on the same sample (Goetschius et al, 2019) and evidence from tracer studies on animal samples that confirms consistent white matter connectivity between the hippocampus and amygdala to the PFC (Barbas, 2015; Barbas &amp; Blatt, 1995). In addition to the PFC regions identified, we will include amygdala as a target region (for hippocampus as seed) as there has been evidence that hippocampus-amygdala connection may be critical in stress response regulation (Houshyar et al, 2013; Owens &amp; Nemeroff, 1991). We will use the maximum likelihood of connectivity for each pair for both hemispheres to create a variable representing white matter connectivity, and subsequently select the 5 most connected regions for the main effect regression analysis with material hardship as the independent variable.

conditions.value:
Subjects will not be assigned to conditions but will be characterized according to material hardship (MH) composite scores (cumulative; developmental age groups). 

Material hardship is measured based on primary caregiver’s responses to the following 8-items: 
(1) Received free meals; 
(2) Did not pay full rent/mortgage; 
(3) Evicted for not paying full rent/mortgage; 
(4) Did not pay full gas/oil/electric bill; 
(5) Borrow money from family/friends to pay bills; 
(6) Move in with people because of financial problems; 
(7) Stay in place not meant for regular housing; 
(8) Did not receive medical care. 

At ages 1, 3, 5, 9, and 15, caregivers indicated whether or not they experienced any of the above hardship within the past year. Responses were coded as 0 (no) or 1 (yes). When mother was not the primary caregiver, father was considered as primary caregiver if child lived with father for at least half of the time. For missing time points, survey data may be imputed or subject excluded if not enough data collected per wave. 

Three material hardship score composites will be computed and utilized as independent variables: 
(1)	Material hardship at each individual age (1, 3, 5, 9, 15); 
(2)	Material hardship at three developmental timing groups (1 and 3, 5 and 9, 15); 
(3)	Cumulative material hardship score, which is computed by the sum of material hardship items across all time points and averaging it by the number of observations collected per subject.

